If you have a lot of end-to-end Cypress tests and want to quickly add a few unit tests, you do not have to bring a second test runner. You can use Cypress to write and run unit tests, and even mock Node modules like fs.readFileSync if needed. Find the full source code for this example in repo https://github.com/bahmutov/cypress-testrail-simple

Example source code that uses fs.readFileSync

const fs = require('fs')
function findCasesInSpec(spec, readFile = fs.readFileSync) {
  ...
}
module.exports = { findCasesInSpec }

Example unit test that passes our stub to replace fs.readFileSync

import { findCasesInSpec } from '../../src/find-cases'

it('finds test case ids', function () {
  const source = `
    it('C101', ...)
  `
  const readFile = cy.stub().returns(source)
  const ids = findCasesInSpec('spec1.js', readFile)
  expect(ids).to.deep.equal([101])
  expect(readFile).to.be.calledWith('spec1.js', 'utf8')
})

In this video, I take the repo https://github.com/robcaldecott/cypress-vite mentioned in the tweet https://twitter.com/robertcaldecott/status/1480848740621688832 and refactor it to use the built-in cy.contains and cy.intercept commands to check the page and stub the network requests. Bonus: we can also merge short tests into one meaningful test. The final tests are

describe("app", function () {
  it("renders the heading", function () {
    cy.intercept('/api/names', ['Bob', 'Alice']).as('names')
    cy.visit("/").its('appReady').should('be.true');
    cy.log('**renders in the loading state**')
    cy.contains('[aria-label=loading]', /loading/i)
    cy.contains('[aria-label=loading]', /loading/i).should('not.exist')
    cy.log('**renders heading**')
    cy.contains('h1', /cypress demo/i)
    cy.wait('@names')
    cy.contains('Bob')
    cy.contains('Alice')
  });

  it("handles errors", function () {
    cy.intercept('/api/names', {forceNetworkError: true})
    cy.visit("/").its('appReady').should('be.true');
    cy.contains(/error fetching names/i)
  });
});

In this video, I show the root reason for the Cypress error "async and sync code" - it happens when you have both a Cypress command and a return statement inside cy.then callback. For example, the following test code inside a Cypress test will fail with an error:

.then(function () {
  cy.wrap('Anna')
   return 'Joe'
})

Cypress is not sure which value do you want to yield from the .then callback: "Anna" or "Joe". The same error happens even if you use something like cy.log

then(function () {
  cy.log('returning Joe')
   return 'Joe'
})

The solution is to never use both Cy commands and a return statement inside the same .then callback. For example, if you want to log a value, attach its own callback 

then(function () {
  cy.log('returning Joe').then(function () {
     return 'Joe'
  })
})

Alternative solution: print in a separate .then

.then(function () {
  cy.log('returning Joe')
})
.then(function () {
   return 'Joe'
})

Alternative solution: Cypress yields the value from its last command. Instead of "return" use cy.wrap command

then(function () {
  cy.log('returning Joe')
   cy.wrap('Joe')
})
See the solutions in my https://glebbahmutov.com/cypress-examples/ under "Yield value" recipe

This video shows how to abstract accessing an element via cy.get(aliasName) by defining a window object property with a getter method. The test looks like it is using "normal" variables, but each access calls the "cy.get" command under the hood. 

// create an aliased element
cy.contains('button[role=tab]', 'Page 1').as('page1')
// magic!
// use "page1" to operate on the element
page1.should('have.attr', 'aria-selected', 'true')

Find the code in the repo https://github.com/bahmutov/emulate-navigation-allow-stopping-pure-css-native-js

This video shows how to abstract working with page elements by storing a reference to them using the cy.as command. Later we can access that element using the cy.get command and passing the alias name

// creating an alias
cy.contains('button[role=tab]', 'Page 1').as('page1')
// using an element alias
cy.get('@page1').should('have.attr', 'aria-selected', 'true')

